Incident Response > [T1]: Structured Approach to Incident Response Phases: Incident Prioritization

Incident Prioritization 

One key aspect of successful IR is resource utilization. No matter how big the IR team is, they have a capacity limit and an intense need to prioritize incidents based on impact severity. A backdoor on the email server incident would never have the same severity as a phishing attack.

Usually, when you create a SIEM detection rule to alert for a specific attack, you set a severity level (e.g., critical, high, medium, low, and informative). These levels help incident responders prioritize what to work on.

Here is a real-world example of using different severity levels to prioritize resources from Symantec Endpoint Security.


Critical thinking and a good understanding of cyber-attacks and business requirements play a huge role, too, when prioritizing alerts. The same incident could have different severity for different organizations. A website takedown for Godaddy would be more critical than for an oil and gas company. GoDaddy's website is one of the most vital assets to the business because it's their primary tool to do business. Unlike oil and gas companies, the website is usually a complementary component of their online presence.

Many factors control the severity level of incidents, such as attack size, targeted assets, and ability to recover. For example, data exfiltration attacks are usually irrecoverable. Once your data leaves your network, it's not yours anymore!

This is a gentle reminder that severity is determined based on business impact, not the security impact. Security is nothing but a business enabler, and business context should steer and define the shape of security operations.
